Lab 06 - User ID Controlled by Request Parameter (Classic IDOR)
Objective
Exploit a horizontal privilege escalation vulnerability to obtain the API key of the user carlos.

Background
Many web applications use user-supplied identifiers to determine which resource should be displayed.

For example:

/my-account?id=wiener
or

/my-account?username=wiener
The application reads the identifier from the request and displays the corresponding user's information.

If the application does not verify that the requested resource belongs to the currently authenticated user, an attacker can simply modify the identifier and access another user's data.

This vulnerability is known as an Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR).

IDOR is a subtype of Broken Access Control and usually results in Horizontal Privilege Escalation.

Vulnerability
Horizontal Privilege Escalation (IDOR)

The application trusted a user-controlled request parameter (id / username) to determine which account to display.

No authorization check was performed to verify that the requested account belonged to the authenticated user.

