Methodology
Step 1 – Identify the User Identifier
Observed that the application used a request parameter to determine which user's profile should be displayed.

Example:

/my-account?id=wiener
Step 2 – Test Parameter Manipulation
Modified the request parameter from:

wiener
to

carlos
Example:

/my-account?id=carlos
Step 3 – Observe the Response
Instead of returning:

403 Forbidden
or

401 Unauthorized
the application displayed Carlos's account.

The response contained Carlos's:

Username
Email
API Key
This confirmed that authorization was missing.

Step 4 – Submit the Solution
Copied Carlos's API key.

Submitted it to the lab solution page.

The lab was successfully solved.

Why the Attack Worked
The application trusted user-controlled input to determine which account should be displayed.

Simplified vulnerable logic:

requested_user = request.GET["id"]

show_profile(requested_user)
No ownership verification was performed.

The secure implementation should verify that the requested account belongs to the authenticated user.

Example:

requested_user = request.GET["id"]

if requested_user != session.user:
    return 403

show_profile(requested_user)
