Root Cause
The application directly trusted a user-controlled object reference without validating ownership.

Authorization checks were missing.

Impact
If exploited in a real-world application, attackers may access:

User profiles
Personal information
API Keys
Bank accounts
Medical records
Customer invoices
Private messages
Internal documents
Depending on the application, an IDOR vulnerability may expose highly sensitive information.

Prevention
Never trust user-supplied identifiers.
Verify ownership before returning any resource.
Use server-side authorization checks for every request.
Retrieve resources using the authenticated session whenever possible.
Implement role-based access control (RBAC) or attribute-based access control (ABAC).
Log and monitor unauthorized access attempts.
